04983nam a22005415i 9780822391500DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223915007 a10.1515/97808223915002doi  a(DE-B1597)553667  a(OCoLC)1224278961  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aLeinaweaver, Jessaca B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Circulation of Children :bKinship, Adoption, and Morality in Andean Peru /cJessaca B. Leinaweaver; ed. by Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b11 illustrations, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations : 4600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Translation -- tIntroduction: Moving Children in Ayacucho -- t1. Ayacucho: Histories of Violence and Ethnography -- t2. International Adoption: The Globalization of Kinship -- t3. Puericulture and Andean Orphanhood -- t4. Companionship and Custom: The Mechanics of Child Circulation -- t5. Superación: The Strategic Uses of Child Circulation -- t6. Pertenecer: Knowledge and Kinship -- t7. Circulating Children, at Home and Abroad -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this vivid ethnography, Jessaca B. Leinaweaver explores “child circulation,” informal arrangements in which indigenous Andean children are sent by their parents to live in other households. At first glance, child circulation appears tantamount to child abandonment. When seen in that light, the practice is a violation of international norms regarding children’s rights, guidelines that the Peruvian state relies on in regulating legal adoptions. Leinaweaver demonstrates that such an understanding of the practice is simplistic and misleading. Her in-depth ethnographic analysis reveals child circulation to be a meaningful, pragmatic social practice for poor and indigenous Peruvians, a flexible system of kinship that has likely been part of Andean lives for centuries. Child circulation may be initiated because parents cannot care for their children, because a childless elder wants company, or because it gives a young person the opportunity to gain needed skills.Leinaweaver provides insight into the emotional and material factors that bring together and separate indigenous Andean families in the highland city of Ayacucho. She describes how child circulation is intimately linked to survival in the city, which has had to withstand colonialism, economic isolation, and the devastating civil war unleashed by the Shining Path. Leinaweaver examines the practice from the perspective of parents who send their children to live in other households, the adults who receive them, and the children themselves. She relates child circulation to international laws and norms regarding children’s rights, adoptions, and orphans, and to Peru’s history of racial conflict and violence. Given that history, Leinaweaver maintains that it is not surprising that child circulation, a practice associated with Peru’s impoverished indigenous community, is alternately ignored, tolerated, or condemned by the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke